node.text:
Microfinance programs built for women excel when they are designed with women. Fundación Paraguaya embodies this approach. 

Hear from their staff and program participants on where they invest their energy. Then, join Whole Planet, Fundación Paraguaya and other sector experts on March 7th for our “Choosing to Challenge” webinar, to honor International Women’s Day.

node.title: Choosing to Challenge: Women Behind the Scenes of Microfinance

node.text:
Serah is a microcredit client of WPF’s microfinance partner SPBD in the Solomon Islands. When she received her first loan from SPBD SI’s Munda branch, Serah bought 15 cooking gas bottles.  This launched her cooking gas bottle refill business.  Each subsequent cycle, she has invested in buying additional bottles.

Cooking gas bottles can be difficult to buy in Munda.  Even now, she often calls her supplier trying to convince them to send more bottles.  After her customers buy a bottle from Serah, they prefer to exchange their empty bottles for refilled bottles with Serah rather than traveling all the way to the port themselves for the refill.  Serah’s husband has a truck that she can use to refill the bottles in bulk.  According to Serah, “In the Solomon Islands, it’s usually the men who are the bosses.  But with our own money, women can also be bosses.” Serah encourages the other women in her community to start their own businesses. #HerBusinessisEssential

node.text:
Since 2014, WPF has been highlighting the hard work of the field staff at our partners through the regional Field Officer Appreciation Awards.  Many of our partners have been regularly participating over the years.  This includes BRAC Sierra Leone,  who has had five field staff recognized for this initiative over the years!  Check out the details below about why these field staff have been recognized. ⁣
⁣
2021: Isatu, in her own words, “Though our operation was suspended for two months following the negative impact of COVID- 19 pandemic in client's livelihoods, I regularly visited the community to sensitize them about COVID-19, through distributing leaflets and posters. I inspire them to use face masks and maintain social distancing.”⁣
⁣
2020: Kadijatu, according to BRAC SL, “She tries to expand her area coverage that helps to cater more clients under the umbrella of financial inclusion.” ⁣
⁣
2019: Hawanatu, in her own words, “The reason why I am enjoying the job is that I have been given the opportunity to provide assistance to community women and my country at large.” ⁣
⁣
2018: Alice, according to BRAC SL, “She has the highest percentage of timely instalment realization  Her good relation with her clients is the main key to her success.” ⁣
⁣
2014: Margaret, according to BRAC SL, “Because of Margaret’s exemplary performance, she is currently undertaking the BMTI training process and is expected to be promoted to Branch Manager in the near future.” ⁣

#repost from one of WPF’s partners in Senegal, @myagro 

While we started by pioneering the use of mobile layaway, myAgro has quickly evolved into an enterprise that provides comprehensive support to smallholder farmers on every level. From delivering high-quality input packages to providing both in-person and remote training, myAgro works with farmers year round to increase yields and income.

#GrowMore #myAgro #foodsecurity #agriculture #fintech #agtech

As Covid-19 border closings in Vietnam have disrupted the imports of animal feed and fertilizer, WPF's partner in Dien Bien has pivoted to assist their farmers to make their own fertilizer and feed. The farmers will raise red worms to transform household waste into fertilizer. ⁣
⁣
In these pictures, Anh Chi Em (ACE), is introducing the project to their members. 
@entrepreneursdumonde

In this photo from a due diligence visit in 2019, MLF Zimbabwe borrowers meet with their group. 

Whole Planet Foundation also partners with @microloanfoundation in Zambia and Malawi.

node.text:
The pandemic has forced many out of work and has complicated people’s limited cash flows as they struggle to pay pending debts. Socially-focused Microfinance organizations like @asei.elsalvador though have offered flexible repayment terms to support their clients during the difficult time.

Elba, a client since before the pandemic, shared that “The pandemic affected me a lot because I used to sell pupusas outside of a local school. When the school closed, I had fewer places to sell. ASEI gave me the opportunity not only to extend my loan repayment period but also to lower the amount due each payment. They adjusted to the change in my situation and helped me a lot.”

Thank you for all you do ASEI!

node.text:
Congratulations to Aurora, for the opening of her new western wear store! She has been a Grameen America member/microloan-borrower since October 2019, just before the global pandemic. Aurora and her family have persevered and adapted through challenges in 2020/2021, including an over 50% drop in her small business’s sales.

Grameen America’s continuation of services for women entrepreneurs across the U.S. has been important support in helping them navigate through these difficult times, via small business loans that reduce the effect of disruptive changes that so many have experienced in the market.

With her latest microloan to help her with her new store location, Aurora is now poised for success. We are inspired, excited, and so happy for you, Aurora.

¡Muchísimas felicidades y éxitos!

node.text:
The cultivation of turmeric, the golden spice belonging to the ginger family, was dwindling in Sri Lanka for decades. But in 2019, the government banned the importation of the root to encourage local production by small-scale farmers. 

Whole Planet’s partner Berendina’s Covid-19 response included livelihood assistance through the distribution of seeds and plant materials, like Turmeric, to clients who needed an urgent rejuvenation of their business activities. These clients are happy to show off some of their big yields!

node.text: The Solomon Islands government has extended the state of public emergency through March 24th.  This impacts most severely the 12% of South Pacific Business Development SI clients who normally work at the public markets, roadside betel nut stalls, cooked food related businesses and clothing stalls.  SPBD SI staff continue to support their clients through continued operations and have been restructuring the loans of affected clients.  Pictured above is Charles, a field officer at SPBD SI.
